# never use fallback values with non-deterministic functions in reducers

Even as a fallback, non-deterministic functions are forbidden:

```typescript
// ❌ FORBIDDEN — fallback is non-deterministic
id: action.input.id || crypto.randomUUID();
timestamp: action.input.timestamp || new Date();

// ✅ REQUIRED — values must always come from input
id: action.input.id;
timestamp: action.input.timestamp;
```

The intent behind the fallback ("provide a default if input is missing") is reasonable, but the implementation violates [[reducer purity requires all dynamic values from action input]]. If the input field is required in the schema, the fallback is unreachable anyway. If it is optional, you need a deterministic default (like `null`), not a generated value.

